'''Sally Wainwright''' is a British [[BAFTA]]-nominated television writer and a playwright. She won 2009 Writer of the Year Award given by the [[Royal Television Society|RTS]] in 2009 for [[Unforgiven (TV series)|''Unforgiven'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/programme-awards-2009 |title=Programme Awards 2009|website=RTS.org.uk}}</ref> She is known for work on the BBC drama's [[Happy Valley (TV series)|Happy Valley]] and [[Last Tango in Halifax]]

==Life==
Wainwright was born in [[Huddersfield]] in 1963 and brought up in Sowerby Bridge where she attended [[Sowerby Bridge High School]].<ref name=sallyyork>[http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/community/nostalgia/sally-wainwright-my-yorkshire-1-3453120 Sally Wainwright: My Yorkshire], Yorkshire Post, retrieved 5 October 2014</ref> Unlike the rest of her family she disliked reading but went to [[York University]] to take English literature. She believes that she may be dyslexic as she has difficulty in reading a complete novel and prefers to just read the interesting bits.<ref name=heroic/>

After university she unsuccessfully took a play to the [[Edinburgh Festival]] but she did find an agent for her writing. Meanwhile she worked as a bus driver. She left the driving job after about 18 months when she was given her first writing debut writing for the Radio 4 series [[The Archers]]. One of her contributions was to write an untypical story for the long running radio soap where the village shop was held up. After that she wrote for [[Coronation Street]] where she feels she developed her story writing skills from 1994 to 1999. She was adopted by [[Kay Mellor]], the writer of the TV series [[Band of Gold (TV series)|Band of Gold]], who encouraged her to leave the safe job on the soap and write. She created at [[At Home with the Braithwaites]] which was a story about a woman who had secretly won the lottery. This TV series wwas nominated for many awards.<ref name=did/> Wainwright says that her strong female flawed characters are almost real to her and they arrive fully formed in her imagination. She likes to control the television that is created and has done some directing and production of her own work<ref name=did>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/e539c4a2#b04k7b73 Sally Wainwright Desert Island Discs], BBC Radio 4, 5 October 2014 broadcast</ref> ensuring that the scenery and dialogue reflects Yorkshire.<ref name=heroic/>

Wainwright based the plot of her series [[Last Tango in Halifax]] on her mother's story. Wainwright's father had died in 2001 after an unsuccessful marriage.<ref name="WainwrightTT">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/10531953/last-tango-in-halifax-wedding-sally-wainwright-love-bbc-derek-jacobi-anne-reid.html|title=My mother's late-life love is charming the nation|first=Charlotte|last=Williamson|date=22 December 2013|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref> Her mother, Dorothy, moved to Oxfordshire to live with her daughter and she rediscovered a lost love, Alec Walker, via [[Friends Reunited]]. With her mother's permission Wainwright developed the story of how she remarried so rapidly and she showed her mother the series before it was broadcast.<ref name=did/>

When she told the story to her colleague [[Nicola Shindler]], Shindler suggested she turn her experience into a television series. Shindler became the series' [[executive producer]].<ref name=WainwrightDM>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2229865/Screenwriter-Sally-Wainwright-Can-fall-love-75.html|title=Can you fall in love at 75? Screenwriter Sally Wainwright on how her mother's sweet late-life romance inspired her new drama|last=Wainwright|first=Sally|work=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|date=9 November 2012|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>

==Original television productions==
Her original television productions include:
*''[[Happy Valley (TV series)|Happy Valley]]'' (2014)<ref name=heroic>[http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jun/06/sally-wainwright-i-like-writing-women-theyre-heroic-happy-valley Sally Wainwright: 'I like writing women, they're heroic'], Vicky Frost,  6 June 2014, The Guardian, retrieved 5 October 2014</ref>
*''[[Last Tango in Halifax]]'' (2012)<ref name=heroic/>
*''[[Scott & Bailey]]'' (2011)<ref name=heroic/>
*''[[Unforgiven (TV series)|Unforgiven]]'' (2009)
*''[[Bonkers (2007 TV series)|Bonkers]]'' (2007)
*''[[Dead Clever]]'' (2007)
*''[[The Amazing Mrs Pritchard]]'' (October 2006)
*''[[ShakespeaRe-Told#The Taming of The Shrew|ShakespeaRe-Told: The Taming of the Shrew]]'' (2005)
*''[[Jane Hall (TV series)|Jane Hall]]'' (2005) (for which she drew on her own experiences as a bus driver in the 1980s<ref name=bus>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article679975.ece |title=In the driving seat |author=Daphne Lockyer |work=The Times |date=1 July 2006 |accessdate=3 March 2011}}</ref>
*''[[The Canterbury Tales (TV series)|The Canterbury Tales]]'' 'The Wife of Bath' (2003)
*''[[Sparkhouse]]'' (2002)
*''[[At Home with the Braithwaites]]'' (2000)<ref name=heroic/>

==Soap operas==
